<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[120,1224,804,1465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
DIAGNOSIS: Bee pupae are rarely described and none of any Xeromelssinae has been so treated. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Torchio, P. F. &amp; B. Burwell" box="[333,658,841,868]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="781 - 789" refId="ref8477" refString="Torchio, P. F., and B. Burwell. 1987. Notes on the biology of Cadegualla occidentalis (Hymenoptera: Colletidae), and a review of colletid pupae. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 80: 781 - 789." type="journal article" year="1987">Torchio and Burwell (1987)</bibRefCitation>
provided information on those available for the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[120,244,879,905]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Colletidae</taxonomicName>
, and noted that the pupa of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Morawitz)" baseAuthorityName="Morawitz" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[599,1001,879,906]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptocephalus">
<emphasis box="[599,857,879,905]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Hylaeus leptocephalus</emphasis>
(Morawitz)
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1871" box="[1055,1214,879,905]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bisinuatus">
<emphasis box="[1055,1214,879,905]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">H. bisinuatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) alone among the representatives of other colletid subfamilies bore a “terminal spine,” possibly a homolog of the median tubercle on tergum 7 of 
<emphasis box="[697,820,953,979]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName box="[697,816,953,979]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Xeromelissa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sielfeldi">X. sielfeldi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, the leg ”spines” reported for pupal 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morawitz" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[236,426,991,1017]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptocephalus">
<emphasis box="[236,426,991,1017]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">H. leptocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to be lacking in 
<emphasis box="[713,839,991,1017]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<taxonomicName box="[713,835,991,1017]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Xeromelissa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sielfeldi">X. sielfeldi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[120,1224,804,1465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">DESCRIPTION: Head shape corresponding closely to that of adult, integument without special tubercles, spines, or setae. Mouthparts with cardo contained in proboscidial fossa, stipes, slightly exserted, and remaining distal elements bending sharply posteriad (fig. 35).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[120,1224,804,1465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Mesosoma shape also corresponding to that of adult; leg segments without spines or tubercles accommodating developing adult setae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[120,1224,804,1465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Metasomal terga without spines or spicules, but more distal ones each with subapical band of vague protuberances (fig. 35) and metasomal tergum 8 with pronounced median tubercle at posterior margin, presumably corresponding to “terminal spine” of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Torchio and Burwell, 1987)" baseAuthorityName="Torchio and Burwell" baseAuthorityYear="1987" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[912,1004,1289,1315]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Hylaeus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Torchio, P. F. &amp; B. Burwell" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="781 - 789" refId="ref8477" refString="Torchio, P. F., and B. Burwell. 1987. Notes on the biology of Cadegualla occidentalis (Hymenoptera: Colletidae), and a review of colletid pupae. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 80: 781 - 789." type="journal article" year="1987">Torchio and Burwell, 1987</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Metasomal sterna each with posterior margin produced downward as transverse ridge (fig. 35, arrows).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
